<font color="#FF0000">A BOWL OF CHERRIES-PITS&amp;ALL</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 11 15:54:00 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chet,<br>
      Am a few posts/days behind, but will note that you are not the only one who wonders if he lost the &quot;fire&quot; sometime.  I look at the fact that not more than 10 members of our 173rd Airborne Assoc. chapter could manage to turn out for our annual memorial service at the Philadelphia Vietnam Memorial, and I feel sick at heart.  The gold star mothers and the color guard from VVA outnumbered us.  That was 3 years ago.  There has been no service since, including last Sunday.<br>
     The term &quot;compassion fatigue&quot; is common these days.  I think something similar has been loose in the veterans' community the past few years.  It's nearly impossible for most to maintain peak enthusiasm for years at a stretch.  The question is whether the commitment and patience (and we Americans are very short on that as a people) to stay with something, say like helping other veterans, is strong enough within us to carry us through the inevitable times of letdown, disappointment, frustration or boredom for the long haul.<br>
     As for me, I'm just to stubborn to quit, even when I feel like shit on the inside.  Have no illusions that this REMF is indispensable, but I'll be there for my brothers even if there is nothing I can do but pray and lend my presence.  I've been living on borrowed time since Vietnam, and I figure I owe somebody for that.  What ever has been painful in that time, is mostly my own fault.  I'm still learning how to live at 52. 
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


